{{one source|date=March 2015}} {{Infobox saint |name=Aaron the Illustrious |birth_date=4th century |death_date= |feast_day=Pentecost Monday, February 3, October 22, and May 23 |venerated_in=[[Syriac Orthodox Church]] |image= |imagesize= |caption= |birth_place=Sarug, [[Osroene|Osrhoene]], [[Mesopotamia]] |death_place= |titles=Monk |beatified_date= |beatified_place= |beatified_by= |canonized_date= |canonized_place= |canonized_by= |attributes= |patronage= |major_shrine= |suppressed_date= |issues= }} '''Aaron the Illustrious''' (also known as '''Aaron of the Nuts''') was a Christian monk of Mesopotamia from the 4th century.
He came from Sarug in [[Osroene|Osrhoene]] and was a disciple of Saint Eugene. He built two monasteries near [[Malatya|Melitene]] in [[Armenia]] in the 4th century. He had a [[feast day]] on [[Whit Monday|Pentecost Monday]] in the [[Syriac Orthodox Church]], and on February 3, October 22, and May 23. He is included in the [[Syrian Martyrology of Rabban Silba]].<ref>*[[Frederick George Holweck|Holweck, F. G.]], ''A Biographical Dictionary of the Saints''. St. Louis, MO: B. Herder Book Co., 1924.</ref>
